      <div class="prose">

        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>HVAC contractors face a persistent software challenge: the tools built for service companies (Jobber, ServiceTitan) are optimized for scheduling technicians and dispatching to service calls, while the tools built for construction (Buildertrend, Procore) handle project-based installation work. Most HVAC companies do both — and need software that serves at least one side well without creating chaos on the other.</p>

        <h2>HVAC service businesses (maintenance, repair, emergency)</h2>
        <p>For HVAC companies where most revenue comes from service calls, maintenance agreements, and system replacements, service management software delivers the most operational value.</p>

        <p><strong>ServiceTitan</strong> is the industry standard for established HVAC service companies. Maintenance agreement tracking, flat-rate pricing presentations in the field, intelligent dispatch, and marketing attribution tools are designed specifically for HVAC and plumbing service businesses. The investment is significant — expect $400–$600+/month plus a multi-week implementation — but the ROI is measurable for companies with 5+ technicians.</p>

        <p><strong>Jobber ($69–$349/mo)</strong> is the right starting point for smaller HVAC service businesses. Scheduling, quoting, invoicing, and online payment work cleanly without ServiceTitan's cost and complexity. Most small HVAC companies start on Jobber and consider ServiceTitan as they scale.</p>

        <h2>Commercial HVAC mechanical subcontractors</h2>
        <p>HVAC mechanical subcontractors doing commercial work — new construction ductwork, commercial system installations, tenant improvement HVAC — need project management tools built for commercial subcontracting. Service dispatch software doesn't apply here.</p>

        <p><strong>Knowify (~$149/mo)</strong> is the best fit for commercial HVAC subs who bill on AIA pay applications, track job costs against a bid, and manage change orders with a GC. The platform is built around the commercial subcontractor workflow, not the service dispatch model. AIA billing, contract management, and job cost tracking against original bid are all native features.</p>

        <h2>Residential HVAC installation</h2>
        <p>HVAC companies focused on residential system installation — new home HVAC design and install, full system replacements, additions — need tools that handle project coordination, scheduling with homebuilder GCs, and client communication.</p>

        <p><strong>Contractor Foreman ($49/mo)</strong> covers estimating, scheduling, and basic project management for small residential installation companies. <strong>Buildertrend ($499/mo)</strong> is appropriate for larger operations that need deeper project management alongside homebuilder clients who expect professional coordination.</p>

